[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alekhine's Defense:"]
[Black "Trampled Cavalry"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36986"]

1. e4 Nf6 {Alekhine's Defense is a provocative counter to 1. e4. Black 
encourages White's pawn to step forward again, and with tempo!} 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 
Nc6 $2 {In this opening Black tries to prove that White's pawn can be 
overextended and weak. This move is taking the concept too far, however! Black 
can improve with 3... d6.} 4. c4 {Black's cavalry will now be hunted!} Nb6 {On 
4... Ndb4, White can continue 5. a3 Na6 6. b4, threatening 7. b5. White's space 
advantage would be overwhelming - especially since Black would be forced to 
cower with 7... Nab8.} 5. d5 $1 Nxe5 {It appears White has blundered a pawn, but 
the e-pawn was merely a sacrifice for the greater good of the position!} 6. c5 
{Pow!} Nbc4 {Black's knight pair is rapidly running out of 'stable' squares (I 
can't believe I just made that pun).} 7. Qd4 {Eying both steeds. Now 8. Bxc4 is 
the threat.} b5 {Black has no other way to support the c4-knight, and moving it 
to a5 would only drop e5.} 8. cxb6 {Best, although 8. b3 is also good.} c5 9. 
Qc3 $1 {Eyes on the prize. Black was hoping to sidetrack his adversary with 9. 
Qxc5? Qxb6.} Ba6 10. Nd2 Nxd2 11. Bxa6 {White wins a piece, as both of Black's 
knights are hanging. If you're an Alekhine's Defense aficionado, don't leave 
your knights out on a limb!} *

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Caro-Kann Defense:"]
[Black "Pawn Punishment"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36987"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {I'm always torn about what to play against the 
Caro-Kann. When your opponent plays this or the French Defense you have a clear 
choice on move three: capture on d5, advance to e5, or play a useful move that 
maintains the tension} ({3. Nc3/3. Nd2; both of which defend e4}) {. All are 
legitimate options! At present, theory considers the text (The Advance 
Variation) to be the most critical test of the Caro-Kann.} Bf5 {Developing the 
bishop outside the pawn chain. Black's next move is normally 4... e6, intending 
French-like development often combined with pressure on White's pawn chain 
with...c6-c5.} 4. h4 {Gaining space on the kingside and preparing a devilish 
ambush. The beauty of this'trap' is that 4. h4 is in fact a legitimate try for 
an advantage! You wouldn't think that moving a rook pawn and stubbornly refusing 
to develop could work in White's favor, but current elite players like Caruana, 
Kramnik, and Topalov along with past greats like Bronstein and Tal have all 
played this line.} e6 $4 {Consistent, but Black was better of with a 
prophylactic move like 4... h5 or 4... h6. Can you figure out why that's the 
case?} 5. g4 $1 {Fix bayonets, and CHAAAAARGE!!} Be4 {Or 5... Bg4 6. h5.} 6. f3 
Bg6 7. h5 {The bishop is trapped. White wins a piece! I have used this trap 
successfully in one over-the-board against a 1400 (this was a LONG time ago:)) , 
and at least a dozen times in online and casual games. Happy hunting!} *

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Caro-Kann Defense: Knight Raid"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36988"]

1. e4 c6 {Poor Caro-Kann Defense! It's a great opening, but it's getting 
hammered in this repertoire:)} 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Ng5 {This 
seemingly nonsensical move is actually highly regarded by modern theory. The 
point is that White's knight will hang over Black's king like the sword of 
Damocles.} h6 $2 6. Ne6 $1 fxe6 $4 {Black needed to play 6... Qa5+ or 6... Qb6, 
although it's clear something has gone wrong if Black cannot capture the 
knight.} 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qxg6# {Another permutation of this trap is 5... Ngf6 6. 
Bd3 h6?, where 7. Ne6! is again correct - this time because of 7... fxe6 8.Bg6#. 
Therefore theory dictates that Black should proceed cautiously with 6... e6 7. 
N1f3 Bd6 8. Qe2 and only now 8... h6, when 9. Ne4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 is a theoretical 
tabiya.} *

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Caro-Kann Defense:"]
[Black "Smothered King"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36989"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 {This is officially called the Modern 
Variation, although the names of World Champions Vasily Smyslov and Anatoly 
Karpov are often deservedly attached as well (both used it quite successfully). 
Black hopes to continue seamlessly with ...Ng8-f6, when a trade on f6 would not 
damage his pawn structure (Nxf6+ Nxf6).} 5. Qe2 {Now THIS is a trappy move! :) 
White blocks his own light-square bishop - something that is usually a no-no.} 
Ngf6 $4 {Oh no! Black reacts mechanically, but 5... Ndf6 or 5. ..e6 were 
needed.} 6. Nd6# {In the blink of an eye, the game is over! This is one of the 
quickest smothered mates you can achieve in chess. Moreover, it occurred after 
fairly normal moves! MegaBase indicates that 37 poor souls have succumbed to 
this mate. A great trap to know!} *

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sicilian Defense:"]
[Black "Smith-Morra Blitzkrieg"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36990"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The Smith-Morra Gambit is White's most combative 
attempt against the Sicilian Defense. White offers a pawn to open lines and 
speed his development.} dxc3 {Personally, I prefer to decline the gambit pawn 
with 3... d3 or 3... Nf6. There's no doubt that acceptance is the critical test, 
however!} 4. Nxc3 {Now come a few natural moves for both sides.} Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 
6. Bc4 {An aggressive post. White eyes the often-weak f7 square.} Nf6 $6 {Again, 
incredibly natural: Black develops in accordance with the age-old maxim'knights 
before bishops.' MegaBase shows that 4... Nf6 has been played close to 1,000 
times, so if you're a Smith-Morra Gambit practitioner you'll want to know how to 
respond!} 7. e5 $1 {Excellent timing! White is a bit better developed, and he 
immediately makes use of this trump.} dxe5 {Even worse is 7.. .Nxe5? 8. Nxe5 
dxe5 9. Bxf7+!, winning the Black queen. Relatively best is 7... Ng4, but the 
majority of games have seen 7... dxe5.} 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 {Also bad for Black is 
8... Kxd8 9. Ng5!, hitting f7.} 9. Nb5 $1 {Patience! It's tempting to capture on 
e5, but threatening 10. Nc7+ is much stronger.} Kd7 $4 {Black needs to find 9... 
Rb8 to stay in the game, although even there White is clearly better after 10. 
Nxe5} ({or even 10. Nc7+!? Kd7 11. Nb5, stranding Black's king in the center}) 
{.} 10. Nxe5+ Ke8 11. Nc7# {Game over! A classic Smith-Morra Gambit trap. If 
you're interested in this opening, I warmly recommend IM Marc Esserman's 
incredible 2012 work'Mayhem in the Morra'.} *

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Accelerated Dragon:"]
[Black "Smothered Queen"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36991"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 {The source game for this trap actually began 2. Ne2 Nc6, but it 
transposed on move 5.} Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 {In the Accelerated Dragon 
Black tries to delay ...d7-d6 and may even venture ...d7-d5 break in a single 
move.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 {Many players automatically respond to ... 
Ng8-f6 with f2-f3, but White need not fear ...Nf6-g4 yet. Therefore he can 
develop his light-square bishop to a desirable square.} O-O 8. Bb3 {Prophylaxis. 
Against FM Andrew Karklins at the 2002 Chicago Open I erred with 8.0-0?!, to 
which Karklins responded with 8... Nxe4!, the center-fork trick} ({9. Nxe4 d5, 
winning back the piece}) {.} Na5 $2 {Hunting down the bishop but inviting a 
brutal response. Better is 8... d6 or 8... a5.} 9. e5 $1 {Black's knight no 
longer stands on c6, so this advance is safe.} Ne8 {Losing. Black's only chance 
to stay in the game is 9... Nxb3, although he is in bad shape after 10. exf6 
Nxa1 11. fxg7. It's also relevant to note that 9... Nh5 runs in to 10. g4!, 
trapping the knight (a common device!).} 10. Bxf7+ {Huh?! Where did this come 
from? One can only imagine Black's shock! Stunned, Black actually resigned in 
the source game, Bastrikov - Shamkovi, Sochi 1958. Instead, the famous encounter 
Fischer - Reshevsky, New York 1958 continued:} Kxf7 {10... Rxf7 or 10... Kh8 
will meet with the same fate.} 11. Ne6 $1 {This is the idea! Black's queen is 
attacked, and the flight squares on c7 and b6 are both covered. The only option 
is to capture the intruder on e6.} dxe6 {If 11... Kxe6, then 12. Qd5+ swiftly 
mates, e.g. 12... Kf5 (only move) 13. g4+ Kxg4 14. Rg1+ Kh4 15. Qe4+ Kh3 16. 
Qg4+ Kxh2 17. Qg2#.} 12. Qxd8 {With just two pieces for the queen GM Samuel 
Reshevsky managed to stagger on until move 42 before capitulating. I cannot 
confirm where I read it, but I'm fairly certain that Fischer - a devourer of 
everything old and new in chess (even in the 'dark ages' of information exchange 
in 1958!) was aware of the Bastrikov - Shamkovi game played the same year. If 
so, this is a striking example of why it pays to be prepared in the opening!} 
1-0

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
