[White "Sicilian Defense:"]
[Black "Overambitious Dragon"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36992"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 {The Dragon Variation, 
wherein Black shoots for a fianchetto of the dark-square bishop.} 6. Be3 Ng4 $4 
{The Dragon has a reputation for producing exciting and tactically rich games, 
but overly ambitious players sometimes blunder with this knight leap. How can 
White punish Black's transgressions?} 7. Bb5+ $1 {A wonderfully disruptive 
check. Now 7... Nc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6+ will see White picking up the rook in 
the corner, so Black may instead try to block on d7.} Bd7 {7... Nd7 would meet 
the same fate, and 7... Qd7 is obviously out of the question.} 8. Qxg4 {If you 
were playing over-the-board and Black now attempted to play 8... Bxg4, you could 
take great pride in informing your opponent that this is illegal! :) White nets 
a clean piece.} *

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Najdorf Variation:"]
[Black "Pawn Truly Poisoned"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36993"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {The Najdorf Variation is 
one of the premier defenses to 1. e4.} 6. Bg5 {An aggressive and popular reply. 
I have most often played this way when up against the Najdorf, as White's 
natural attacking scheme of f2-f4, Qd1-f3, 0-0-0, Bf1-d3, and Rh1-e1 appeals to 
me.} e6 7. f4 Qb6 {The Poisoned Pawn Variation! In this line Black makes a 
daring raid on the b2-pawn. Theory revolves around 8. Qd2 and 8. Qd3 at this 
stage.} 8. a3 {Back in the late'90s/early'00s I was an up-and-coming young 
player at the Chess Castle in Minneapolis, MN. I distinctly recall one 30-minute 
club game against an 1800 where I played this modest move...} Qxb2 $4 {...and my 
opponent fell for it! Black usually snatches the pawn in this line, but do you 
see the point of White's previous move?} 9. Na4 $1 {That's it! Black's queen has 
been ensnared, as 8. a3 took away the flight square on b4.} Qxa1 10. Qxa1 Nxe4 
$2 {Another mistake, but Black is down far too much material anyways.} 11. Nb6 
{Black resigned. I won't give my opponent's name in order to protect the 
innocent:) Truth be told, 8. a3 is not a particularly great move, but it may be 
worth a shot. An opponent may grab the b2-pawn without thinking!} *

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Petroff Defense: Future"]
[Black "World Champion Caught!"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36994"]

1. e4 {1988 was the year Vishwanathan Anand achieved his Grandmaster title. 
Though he would go on to become undisputed World Champion in 2007, this trap 
demonstrates that even future title contenders are not immune to traps!} e5 2. 
Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 {Anand is well aware of the pitfalls of 3..Nxe4? and instead 
prefers the theoretically improved move.} 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 {White offers a 
trade of knights. If Black accepts with 5... Nxc3, then White continues 6. dxc3, 
intending to develop the dark-square bishop to e3/f4, play Qd1-d2, and castle 
queenside. Many games have been contested in this line.} Bf5 $4 {Developing and 
defending e4 but Anand's choice loses the game!} 6. Qe2 $1 {Black resigned in 
Zapata - Anand, Biel 1988. Easily the shortest loss of Anand's professional 
career! Since White is threatening 7. Nxe4, Black only has a couple options. 
7... d5 would lose the knight to 8. d3 (pinning and winning), so that only 
leaves one move:} Qe7 7. Nd5 $1 {Black has unpinned the knight, but White 
strikes with a multi-purpose knight centralization.} Qd8 {Even worse is 7... 
Qe6? 8. Nxc7+ with a royal fork!} 8. d3 {The knight perishes.} 1-0

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Petroff Defense:"]
[Black "Symmetry Shattered"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36995"]

1. e4 {In high school I worked a few summers with IM Sean Nagle at the Minnesota 
Renaissance Festival. Our job for 10 hours on Saturdays and Sunday in 
August/September was to take on all comers at the chess booth! We dressed in 
peasant costumes and played hundreds of games each day against festival patrons 
of all ages and skill levels (most were very casual players, of course) . At the 
end of the day we were both exhausted and usually caked with dirt, as the 
festival was outdoors! The following trap is one I used in easily 50+ games 
against unwary opponents.} e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {The Petroff Defense has a bit of a 
lame reputation, but you can't deny that it presents a direct question: can 
White gain an advantage in a symmetrical position?} 3. Nxe5 Nxe4 $6 {Consistent, 
but if you play the Petroff you know that Black must preface this capture 3... 
d6, booting the knight.} 4. Qe2 $1 {Here, most of my Renaissance Festival 
opponents noticed that continuing symmetrically with 4... Qe7 would end 
disastrously after 5. Qxe4 Qxe5??} ({incidentally, best is 5... d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. 
dxe5, when Black can still fight a pawn down}) {. Thus, many of them would play 
the following:} Nf6 $4 {Saving the knight, but the cure is worse than the 
disease!} 5. Nc6+ {Discovered check!} Qe7 {Or 5... Bxe7, whereupon the queen 
falls on d8.} 6. Nxe7 {White wins a decisive amount of material. Every 1. e4 
player should be aware of this one!} *

[Event "11 Opening Traps with 1.e4"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Italian Game: Hungarian"]
[Black "Disappointment"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "11-opening-traps-with-1e4/course/570, variation/36996"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Be7 {The Hungarian Defense is a solid albeit slightly 
passive way of meeting the Italian Game. Black overprotects the g5 square and 
keeps his bishop back, avoiding (for instance) potential attacks with c2-c3 and 
d2-d4.} 4. d4 {The theoretically prescribed treatment. Unlike 3. ..Bc5 Black is 
not controlling d4, and in contrast to 3... Nf6 there is no pressure on e4 to 
concern us. Thus, White is free to break in the center. The goal is to open 
lines!} exd4 {Playable, although reinforcing the center with 4. ..d6 is more in 
the spirit of this defense.} 5. c3 {In 2012 I was hired as a coach for the US 
team at the World Youth Chess Championships in Maribor, Slovenia, and one of my 
charges was a girl participating in the Under 8 section. During our preparations 
for one of her games we noticed that her opponent consistently played the 
Hungarian Defense for Black. As such, I acquainted our player with the following 
line:} dxc3 $2 {Too greedy! Black is opening too many lines. According to the 
engine, 5... Na5 is best.} 6. Qd5 {Ouch! Suddenly, Black can scarcely defend 
f7.} Nh6 {Virtually forced. Note that the bishop on e7 disrupts Black's 
coordination, as...Qd8-e7 is not possible.} 7. Bxh6 {Removing the defender! In 
the aforementioned World Youth game Black resigned at this point. I was happy 
that our player won but couldn't help but feel bad for the little girl on the 
other side of the board! However, she could have continued:} O-O 8. Bxg7 {White 
should return the piece, as 8. Bc1 (trying to save the bishop and protect 
against ...c3xb2) runs in to 8. ..Nb4!, attacking the queen and threatening 9... 
Nc2+.} Kxg7 {Also best. If 8... Nb4, then 9. Qe5 is strong, defending g7. On 
8... c2, 9. Bh6 is good.} 9. Nxc3 $16 {White has an advantage in view of Black's 
exposed king, although Black has staved off the worst of it. White has a strong 
80% score from this position. Interestingly, the computer advocates for 6. Qb3 
instead of 6. Qd5, although I know of no games where this was actually played.} 
*

